Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you don’t have symptoms.

Senegal has put measures in place to limit the spread of coronavirus (COVID-19).
For information on how to return to the UK from Senegal, see Return to the UK
Entry and borders
A ban on all commercial air transport is in place until 31 May, with the exception of flights with ‘special authorisation’. You should check with your airline before travelling.
Senegal’s borders with neighbouring countries are closed, except for goods vehicles in the case of Mali and Guinea.
Local measures
A national state of emergency is in place until 2 June. This includes:
a curfew between 8pm and 6am
the compulsory use of face masks in government buildings, private sector workplaces, shops and markets as well as all forms of transport. You are strongly advised to wear a face mask in public even when travelling alone in your own vehicle
a ban on gatherings and demonstrations on public highways
bans on the movement of people, vehicles and goods in given locations or times
banning public or private meeting spaces as well as all public or private gatherings that could lead to civil disturbance
Travel between regions is prohibited without authorisation. If you are travelling between Senegal’s regions you will need to get authorisation from the Ministry of Interior.
Some supermarkets and markets are now restricting the days they open in Dakar and elsewhere.
Thirteen hotels in Dakar are not open to the public as they are being used as part of the emergency response to COVID-19. These are: Virage, Arc-En-Ciel, Étoile du Lac, Chez Salon, Pullman-Teranga, Ngor Diarama, Ibis-Novotel, Lagon, Savana, Ndiambour, Terrou-Bi, Calao and Fleur de Lys.
See the Ministry of Health website for further information on the Senegalese government response.
You should comply with any additional screening measures put in place by the authorities. Keep up to date with information from your tour operator, transport or accommodation provider on the impact on any existing travel plans.
Road travel
There are limits on the number of passengers per vehicle. A maximum of three people, including the driver, can travel in a five-seater car.
Further information
The government of Senegal is encouraging those with any information or concerns about coronavirus to call +221 800 00 50 50.
See the TravelHealthPro website for further advice on travel abroad and reducing spread of respiratory viruses during the COVID-19 pandemic.
